				\begin{document}$$P=\frac{\#(null < obs)+\frac{\#(null=obs)}{2}}{1000}.$$\end{document}P=#(null<obs)+#(null=obs)21000.

We built our null models by assuming that growth or mortality are time-independent which would be the case if extreme climate events were not driving inter-annual variations in growth or mortality. For the growth model, we sampled from replacement a pool of BAGR from surviving trees in a given plot over all years. In this model, mortality is allowed to vary year on year. For the mortality model, mortality is similarly assumed to be constant over the period of our analysis. The instantaneous mortality rate m for each plot is then computed from \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
